## Running the Brain

```bash
# From this directory:
neurogrim score --registry .claude/brain-registry.json
neurogrim health --registry .claude/brain-registry.json
neurogrim narrate --hat visionary --registry .claude/brain-registry.json
neurogrim validate --registry .claude/brain-registry.json
```

All CMDBs ship as honest stubs at score 50; the unified score reflects the
all-stub state. As sensors are authored (and CMDBs start carrying real
signal), the score becomes meaningful.

## Cultural substrate

`.claude/culture.yaml` is byte-identical to the canonical LSP Brains
federation copy. Five values applied as invariants — `positivity`,
`integrity`, `honesty`, `critical_but_kind`, `respect`. They can only
tighten, never loosen. When working in this repo, agents honor these
invariants in every output.

## The PostToolUse hook

`.claude/settings.local.json` (gitignored) wires a PostToolUse hook that
records every Skill invocation to `.claude/brain/invocation-ledger.jsonl`.
This is the substrate for the `operator-calibration` primitive (LSP Brains
spec §17.12) — capturing operator dispositions on agent skill invocations.

The hook script lives at `scripts/record-skill-invocation.sh` (committed,
self-contained — uses `CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR` env, no external deps).

## What agents working here should know

1. **Abstract domains are first-class.** They observe project state through
   the same sensory protocol as code-project domains. Treat them with the
   same rigor.
2. **CMDBs at score 50 are honest unknown.** Don't "fix" them by inflating
   scores; sensors will produce real signal when authored.
3. **The cultural substrate applies after hats and human-comms.** Per
   spec §14.4, culture is a floor that can only tighten.
4. **Author project-specific skills via `neurogrim skill new <name>`.**
   The bundled skills cover general-purpose workflows; project-specific
   methodology belongs in operator-authored skills.

